2021 Capital BikeShare Data Exploration and Visualization¶

by Stimson¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Capital Bikeshare, provides the trips data around Washington DC Metro Area from the year 2010. Each quarter, we publish downloadable files of Capital Bikeshare trip data. For the analysis we explore on 2021 data. The data includes:

  • Duration – Duration of trip
  • Start Date – Includes start date and time
  • End Date – Includes end date and time
  • Start Station – Includes starting station name and number
  • End Station – Includes ending station name and number
  • Bike Number – Includes ID number of bike used for the trip
  • Member Type – Indicates whether user was a "registered" member (Annual Member, 30-Day Member or Day Key Member) or a "casual" rider (Single Trip, 24-Hour Pass, 3-Day Pass or 5-Day Pass) This data has been processed to remove trips that are taken by staff as they service and inspect the system, trips that are taken to/from any of our “test” stations at our warehouses and any trips lasting less than 60 seconds (potentially false starts or users trying to re-dock a bike to ensure it's secure).

NOTE: The 3-Day Membership replaced the 5-Day Membership in Fall 2011

def data_info(data):
    """
    This function helps in displaying the basic descriptive information
        ⁍ Shape
        ⁍ Number of duplicate values
        ⁍ unique index
        ⁍ Missing values in column
        ⁍Datatype of each column
    
    Parameter:
    data: Dataframe that requires the descriptive information
    """
    
    # Shape
    print("Shape of data: {}".format(data.shape))
    
    #Duplicates
    print("\n\nDuplicates : ",sum(data.duplicated()))
    
    #Checking the index is finite
    if data.index.is_unique:
        print("\n\nThe index is \033[1;3m unique \033[0m")
    else:
        print('\n\nThe index is \033[1;3m not unique \033[0m')
    
    # print only missing values
    print(" \033[1;3m \n\nMissing values:  \033[0m")
    missing_col =[]
    for col in data.columns:
        if data[col].isna().sum() > 0:
            print(col,':',data[col].isna().sum())
            missing_col.append(col)
    if len(missing_col) == 0:
        print('No missing values')
    print('\n\n')
    
    # Datatype
    print("\033[1;3m Datatype of each colum  \033[0m \n ",data.dtypes)
    
    #\033[1;3m' and '\033[0m

start = time.time()

# Calculating the kms using the lat and long
def distance(lat1, lat2, lon1, lon2):
     
    # The math module contains a function named
    # radians which converts from degrees to radians.
    lon1 = radians(lon1)
    lon2 = radians(lon2)
    lat1 = radians(lat1)
    lat2 = radians(lat2)
      
    # Haversine formula
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon / 2)**2
 
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a))
    
    # Radius of earth in kilometers. Use 3956 for miles
    r = 6371
      
    # calculate the result
    return round((c * r),2)

#calculating Distance travelled (Km)
df['travel_distance'] = df.apply(lambda row :distance(row['start_lat'], row['end_lat'], row['start_lng'], row['end_lng']),axis =1 )

end = time.time()
print('Runtime : ',round((end - start),2),"s\n")

Visualization¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original combined data contains approximately 27,49,881 individual trip records with 13 variables collected. The variables can be divided into 3 major categories:

  • Trip details
  • station informations
  • user type
  • Dervied columns to assist exploration

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm exploring the bike trips' duration along user characteristics, i.e.

  • When do they ride?
  • How far do they go?
  • Which stations are most popular?
  • What days of the week are most rides taken on?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Each trip's start date/time and duration information will help understanding how long a trip usually takes and when.
  • The user type column (member_casual) helps in analysing the behavioural pattern between different groups. # Univariate Exploration

def set_custom_palette(series, highlight_color = 'turquoise', other_color = 'lightgrey', highlight = 'Max'):
    
    if highlight == 'Max':
        val = series.max()
    if highlight == 'Min':
        val = series.min()
    pal = []
    for item in series:
        if item == val:
            pal.append(highlight_color)
        else:
            pal.append(other_color)
    return pal
 
# Barchart
def barplot(x , y, color = '#79DAE8', orient = None, order = None, palette = None, xlabel = None, ylabel = None, title = None, show_values = False):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (15,8))
    ax = sns.barplot(x=x, y = y,  color = color, order=order,palette = palette, orient = orient)
    if show_values:   
        ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0])
    if xlabel is not None:
        plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    if ylabel is not None:
        plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)
    sns.despine(bottom = True, left = True)
    plt.show()
